 The Ministry of Health on Tuesday announced that 35 people
have tested positive for COVID-19 from a sample size of 4,246 tested in the
last 24 hours, marking a positivity rate of 0.8%. In a statement issued on Wednesday, the Ministry of Heath said the total confirmed
positive cases now stand at 254,816 while cumulative tests so far conducted are 2,811,260.  "From the cases, 33 are Kenyans while two are foreigners; 22
are males and 13 are females, while the youngest is five years and the oldest
is 79 years," reads the statement. The cases were distributed across various counties namely; Nairobi
13, Nakuru 4, Nyamira 4, Kakamega 3, Baringo 2, Isiolo 2, Bungoma 1, Kisumu 1,
Nyeri 1, Siaya 1, Trans Nzoia 1, Turkana 1 and Uasin Gishu 1. The ministry said 26 patients recovered from the disease,
with 22 from the Home-Based Isolation and Care program while 4 were discharged
from various health facilities countrywide. Total recoveries stand at 248,018. Two people succumbed to the disease pushing the cumulative
fatalities to 5,332. “A total of 346 patients are currently admitted in various
health facilities countrywide, while 973 are under the Home-Based Isolation and
Care program,” read a statement signed by Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi
Kagwe. “20 patients are in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU), 9 of whom
are on ventilatory support and 11 on supplemental oxygen. No patient is under
observation.” The Ministry added: “Another 112 patients are separately on
supplemental oxygen with 111 of them in the general wards. One patient is in
the High Dependency Unit (HDU).” The CS also noted an increase in the number of persons turning
up for vaccination attributing the same to the New Directives and Measures
issued by the Cabinet Secretary over the weekend. “For the first time since the vaccination exercise kicked
off, we have recorded the highest number of vaccines administered on a single
day. As of November 23rd 2021, we recorded a total of 103,506 vaccines
administered, 53,506 are first doses while 50,000 are second doses,” he stated. The CS also said a total of 6,597,597 vaccines had been
administered across the country as of November 23, 2021. Of these, 4,087,317 were partially vaccinated while those
fully vaccinated were 2,510,280. The uptake of the second dose among those who
received their first dose was at 57.1%.  The proportion of adults fully vaccinated was 9.0%.